---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "cowork-what")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        <strong>Claude Cowork</strong> is for running many tasks at once, in the background.
        Instead of opening a terminal and watching one conversation, you submit work from a webpage
        and come back later to review the results.
      </p>

      <h2>The mental shift</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Claude Code = pair programming.</strong> You and Claude work on the same thing, together, in real time.</li>
        <li><strong>Claude Cowork = delegating.</strong> "Fix this bug. Add this small feature. Update these dependencies." Each goes off and works on its own; you check in when convenient.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why this is useful</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Small chores add up.</strong> Eight 15-minute fixes done in parallel = two hours saved.</li>
        <li><strong>No context-switching cost for you.</strong> You stay focused on the hard problem.</li>
        <li><strong>Each task is isolated.</strong> One task's experiments can't break another's.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>A worked example</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p style="margin-top: 0;"><strong>Monday morning.</strong> You open Cowork on the web and submit three tasks against your project:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>"Bump all dependencies to their latest minor versions and run tests."</li>
          <li>"Add a loading spinner to the upload form."</li>
          <li>"The footer is missing a copyright year — fix it."</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Each task spins up its own copy of your project (a sandboxed branch). Claude works on each in parallel.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>After your coffee:</strong> three pull requests are waiting. You skim each, merge the good ones, comment on the one that misunderstood, and move on.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Think "interns, not contractors".</strong> Cowork is best at well-scoped tasks with clear success criteria.
        For ambiguous, design-heavy work, sit down with it in Claude Code instead.
      </div>

      <Reveal q="Where does Cowork run?">
        On Anthropic's infrastructure — your code is checked out into a temporary sandbox, the work happens there,
        and you get a diff/PR back. Your local machine isn't involved.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Does it need GitHub?">
        It works most naturally with a git host (GitHub or similar) because tasks come back as pull requests.
        Connect your repo once, then submit tasks at will.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
